`render/` converts resolved `TypedEntry` templates (output of the type-resolution pass) into Plover dictionary entries — `(stroke, "{^}...{^}")` pairs — and is the last stage before dictionary output. Depending on this subtree buys two public entry points per profile (`render_plain`/`build_plain_dict`, `render_smart`/`build_smart_dict`) plus the shared `BuildResult` type; callers don't need to know about tokenization, movement computation, or Plover's affix syntax.

All real logic lives in `mod.rs`: tokenize → (optionally) drop_trailing_closers → coalesce → interpret/movement → wrap. `plain.rs` and `smart.rs` are pure profile selection — each is a couple one-line wrappers around `mod.rs`'s `entry_events`/`wrap`/`build_dict`, differentiated only by which `crate::editor` constant (`PLAIN` vs `SMART`) they pass in. A change to what `PLAIN` or `SMART` mean in `crate::editor` silently changes output here with no corresponding code change in this subtree — that's the main risk when editing across this boundary. The one behavioral fork keyed on profile inside shared code is `drop_trailing_closers`, gated on `b.auto_close`: only `SMART` strips trailing auto-paired closers/quotes from the token stream, trusting the editor to supply them; `PLAIN` always types closers explicitly. Non-terminal (type-append intermediate) entries bypass this fork entirely and render identically under both profiles via `non_terminal_text`.

Collision detection in `build_dict` only compares each stroke's new value against the immediately-prior value stored for that key, not full history — a same-stroke sequence A, B, A flags the B collision but not the third occurrence. `OrderedMap` output preserves insertion order (not stroke order), which downstream JSON emission depends on. Both profiles fail identically via `RenderError` on unresolved template chunks or movement-compilation errors, since both funnel through the same `mod.rs` functions.